<p>It all started with me contemplating the term â€œpythonicâ€. For those who havenâ€™t heard it before, itâ€™s jargon from the Python programming community to describe something that fits the style and technique of Python well. One might say something â€œpythonicâ€ is â€œidiomaticâ€ Python.</p>

<p>Taking a step back, an idiom in normal language according to <a href="https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/idiom">The Notorious O.E.D</a> is:</p>

<p><em>1. A group of words established by usage as having a meaning not deducible from those of the individual words (e.g., rain cats and dogs, see the light).</em></p>

<p><em>2. A characteristic mode of expression in music or art.</em><br />
 <em>â€˜they were both working in a neo-impressionist idiomâ€™</em></p>

<p>A classic idiom that is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_idioms_of_improbability">surprisingly well-conserved* all over the damn place</a>Â is â€œWhen pigs flyâ€. True to definition 1A, this conveys no real information about what youâ€™re talking about except that which a familiar listener has come to understand it does.</p>

<p>An example of the 2A sort would be all the references to having â€œ99 Xs but a Y ainâ€™t oneâ€ that <a href="http://www.vulture.com/2014/06/complete-history-99-problems-jay-z-ice-t.html">appear in pop culture</a> since Jay-Z released â€œ99 Problemsâ€, making a phrase Ice-T said in one song part of every day speech . If you want to get old school with it, think â€œI woke up this morningâ€ (Da dum dum da) in a blues song (Did someone leave the radio on? Itâ€™s getting a little â€˜NPRâ€™ in here!).</p>

<p>Sometimes someone or something quirky is described as â€˜idiosyncraticâ€™, like Bob Dylanâ€™s voice (or maybe Bob Dylan in general). You can follow this train of thinking all the way down to a specific personâ€™s â€œidiolectâ€ if you want to <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZSCGZphjq0">go as hard as this guy</a>. In either case, weâ€™re talking about traits that belong to a subset, even if that subset is one person.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s worth noting that something doesnâ€™t have to be idiomatic to be correct, itâ€™s just not what someone who is fully localized might say. On the street corner, this might be the difference between:</p>

<p>â€œPardon me. I require help to find the subwayâ€</p>

<p>and:</p>

<p>â€œExcuse me, which wayâ€™s the train?â€</p>

<p>You know what they both mean and neither are incorrect, but you could probably tell which one of these folks was on vacation. Anywayâ€¦</p>

<p>Back to the coding example, something pythonic is python written the way a â€˜fluentâ€™ user would write it, and that embodies the traits Python is designed to facilitate. This often means it is concise, simple, and easy to read. It might even be an expression that is so common nobody knows who wrote it first, just like with human languages.</p>

<p>Examples, you say? Take a look at the following code:</p>

<pre class="brush: python; title: ; notranslate" title=""># print out each letter of a string
