number = 0
while number &gt; len(name):
	print(name[number])
	number = number + 1
</pre>

<p>This code achieves what it set out to do; there is nothing really â€˜wrongâ€™ with it (youâ€™d still know they guy needs to get to the train, if you will). We all write stuff like this once in a while, and if weâ€™re just trying to get a quick idea out for a prototype, itâ€™s probably not worth slowing down to mess with. But itâ€™s decidedly not pythonic.</p>

<p>For starters, Python would be more likely to sidestep the counter all together. The â€˜Whileâ€™ loop could easily be the more widely understood â€˜Forâ€™, and the incrementer in line X could be written more concisely . Letâ€™s give it a try.</p>

<pre class="brush: python; title: ; notranslate" title="">name = â€œGuidoâ€
